        <h2>Making the Right Financial Decisions as a First-Time Buyer</h2>
        <p>Buying your first home involves several major financial decisions beyond simply choosing a property. Three of the most consequential are whether to rent or buy, which savings vehicle to use, and whether to lock in a fixed or variable mortgage rate. Each choice has long-term implications for your finances, and the right answer depends on your personal situation.</p>

        <h3>Rent vs. Buy: When Does Buying Make Sense?</h3>
        <p>The rent-versus-buy decision comes down to how long you plan to stay, your local market conditions, and the opportunity cost of tying up your money in a down payment. Generally, buying becomes financially advantageous if you plan to stay in the home for at least five years. That timeframe allows you to absorb closing costs and begin building meaningful equity. In the short term, renting can be cheaper when you factor in maintenance, property taxes, and insurance that homeowners pay.</p>
        <p>Over the long term, <a href="https://www.cmhc-schl.gc.ca/consumers/home-buying/mortgage-loan-insurance" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">CMHC data</a> consistently shows that homeownership builds wealth through forced savings (every payment reduces your mortgage) and property appreciation. However, buying a home you cannot comfortably afford is worse than renting. Use the rent-vs-buy comparison tool above to run the numbers for your specific situation.</p>

        <h3>FHSA vs. RRSP Home Buyers' Plan: Which Is Better?</h3>
        <p>Canada offers two powerful tax-advantaged programs for first-time home buyers saving for a down payment. The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/first-home-savings-account.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">First Home Savings Account (FHSA)</a> lets you contribute up to $8,000 per year to a lifetime maximum of $40,000. Contributions are tax-deductible, growth is tax-free, and withdrawals for a qualifying home purchase are completely tax-free. There is no repayment requirement.</p>
        <p>The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/rrsps-related-plans/what-home-buyers-plan.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">RRSP Home Buyers' Plan (HBP)</a> allows you to withdraw up to $60,000 per person from your RRSP for a home purchase. The withdrawal is tax-free, but you must repay the full amount to your RRSP over 15 years or include the unpaid portion as taxable income. The strongest strategy for most buyers is to use both programs simultaneously, which provides access to up to $100,000 per person — or $200,000 per couple — in tax-advantaged savings.</p>

        <h3>Fixed vs. Variable Mortgage Rates</h3>
        <p>A fixed-rate mortgage locks in your interest rate for the entire term (typically five years), giving you predictable payments regardless of what happens in the economy. A variable-rate mortgage fluctuates with the <a href="https://www.bankofcanada.ca/rates/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Bank of Canada's policy rate</a>, meaning your payments can rise or fall during your term. The five-year fixed rate is the most popular choice among first-time buyers because it offers certainty during a period when budgets tend to be tight.</p>
        <p>Historically, variable rates have saved borrowers money roughly 60% of the time compared to fixed rates over the same period. However, the savings come with risk — if rates spike, your payments increase (or your amortization extends). First-time buyers with limited financial cushion may find the certainty of a fixed rate more valuable than the potential savings of a variable rate.</p>

        <h3>Can I use both the FHSA and RRSP HBP together?</h3>
        <p>Yes. You can combine both programs for up to $100,000 per person in tax-free funds for your home purchase — that is $200,000 per couple. The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/first-home-savings-account.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">FHSA</a> contribution never needs to be repaid. The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/rrsps-related-plans/what-home-buyers-plan.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">HBP</a> withdrawal must be repaid to your RRSP over 15 years, starting the second year after your withdrawal. Missing a repayment means that year's required amount is added to your taxable income.</p>

        <h3>Is a variable rate risky for first-time buyers?</h3>
        <p>Variable rates carry more uncertainty than fixed rates. If interest rates rise, your payments increase or your amortization extends, meaning you pay more interest over the life of the mortgage. If your budget is tight and you cannot absorb a payment increase of several hundred dollars per month, a fixed rate provides safer, more predictable cash flow. That said, if you have financial flexibility and a longer time horizon, a variable rate has historically offered savings more often than not.</p>
